The provided Tundra code is correct as per the given conditions and values.
values. It checks if the user score in report object is greater than passMa
passMark, then it prints "review". Otherwise, it prints "pass". In this cas
case, as 68 (user's score) isn't more than 70 (pass mark), the program shou
should print "pass", not "review" as expected.

If you want to change the output based on conditions and ensure that correc
correct output is produced, please provide a different condition in place o
of `report.user.score > report.passMark` so it could be evaluated either tr
true or false based on your needs. 

For example: if we have different passMarks for users with score > 90 (outs
(outstanding), 80-89 (excellent) and anything below 79 (poor), you can use 
nested if conditions like this:

```Tundra
val report = {
  user: {
    name: "Ada",
    score: 68
  },
  passMark: 70, // changing the pass mark here will change outcomes.
};

if (report.user.score > report.passMark) {
  if(report.user.score > 90){
     print("outstanding");
  } else if(report.user.score >= 80){
     print("excellent");
  } else{
    print("poor");  
  }
} else {
  print("pass");
}
```
